    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE - 9800 - SINGLE REDUCTION, SINGLE SPEED AXLES: SPICER D135-S,
        F155-S, F170-S SERIES - DISASSEMBLE - PINION
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc id="hl1401404" svcproctype="disassemble" graphiccount="9">
        <title>PINION</title>
        <para>Refer to
            <hotlnk xrefid="f1401419">Figure 19.</hotlnk>
        </para>
        <figure id="f1401419" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1401419" filename="../figg14/G1401419.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
            <caption>Figure 19. Pinion - Exploded View</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove pinion cage bolts which hold the pinion assembly to the carrier housing (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1401420">Figure 20</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1401420" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1401420" filename="../figg14/G1401420.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 20. Pinion - Cage Bolt Removal</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove pinion and cage assembly from the carrier housing (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1401421">Figure 21</hotlnk>). If difficulty is encountered in removing the pinion
                assembly from the carrier housing, place a brass drift on the inner end of the pinion gear and tap
                lightly.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1401421" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1401421" filename="../figg14/G1401421.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 21. Pinion and Cage Assembly Removal</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Retain shims for possible use during reassembly.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Mount pinion assembly in a soft jawed vise, holding the yoke stationary, and remove the
                cotter pin, nut, and washer (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1401422">Figure 22</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1401422" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1401422" filename="../figg14/G1401422.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 22. Cotter Pin, Nut and Washer Removal</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the end yoke using a suitable puller.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the pinion gear from the cage assembly.</para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>It may be necessary to tap the outer end of the pinion gear with a soft hammer. Replace the
                        pinion nut, flush with the end of the pinion, so damage to the threads does not occur.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Located between the pinion bearings is a selective spacer, used for pinion bearing preload (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1401423">Figure 23</hotlnk>). Retain this spacer for possible use in reassembly.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1401423" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1401423" filename="../figg14/G1401423.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 23. Selective Spacer</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove old pinion seal and discard. Always replace it with a new seal at time of
                reassembly.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Lift out outer pinion bearing cone.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove inner pinion bearing cup, using a suitable adapter and press or puller (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1401424">Figure 24</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1401424" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1401424" filename="../figg14/G1401424.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 24. Inner Pinion Bearing Cup Removal</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>Do not nick the bearing bore.</para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove outer pinion bearing cup (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1401425">Figure 25</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1401425" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1401425" filename="../figg14/G1401425.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 25. Outer Pinion Bearing Cup Removal</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>Do not nick the bearing bore.</para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove pinion roller bearing from the end of the pinion (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1401426">Figure 26</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1401426" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1401426" filename="../figg14/G1401426.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 26. Pinion Roller Bearing Removal</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove inner bearing cone from the pinion gear (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1401427">Figure 27</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1401427" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1401427" filename="../figg14/G1401427.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 27. Inner Bearing Cone Removal</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
